<h2 id="what-is-vagaro">📱 What Is Vagaro?</h2>

Vagaro launched in 2009 as a salon booking platform and has evolved into a full-service business management system serving spas, salons, fitness studios, and wellness centers. The platform handles online booking, POS, payroll, marketing, and inventory management within a single ecosystem.

The platform now serves over 220,000 businesses globally, with particular strength in the hair salon and day spa segments. Their 2025 updates introduced AI-powered booking optimization and enhanced HIPAA compliance features for med spa operators.

Vagaro operates on a tiered pricing model based on the number of bookable calendars, making it predictable for operators scaling their provider count. The marketplace integration drives organic client acquisition—something Boulevard doesn't offer.

<h2 id="what-is-boulevard">🏢 What Is Boulevard?</h2>

Boulevard entered the market in 2016 targeting premium salons and spas frustrated with clunky legacy software. The platform positions itself as the "client experience platform" rather than just booking software, emphasizing front-desk workflows, sophisticated membership management, and detailed analytics.

Boulevard's client list reads like a who's-who of premium beauty brands: Drybar, Madison Reed, and numerous high-end med spa groups. Their 2025-2026 roadmap delivered major infrastructure improvements including real-time multi-location inventory sync and enterprise API access.

The platform requires custom pricing conversations for most implementations, though their Essentials tier provides an entry point for smaller operations. Boulevard's strength lies in the details—the checkout flow, the client communication sequences, the reporting granularity.

<h2 id="our-experience">🔬 Our Experience Managing Both Platforms</h2>

Our team has managed thousands of business locations across the beauty and wellness industry. We've migrated spa groups from Mindbody to Vagaro, from Vagaro to Boulevard, and yes, from Boulevard back to Vagaro when the math stopped making sense.

Here's what breaks at scale with Vagaro: reporting across locations becomes a manual nightmare around location 8-10. You'll find yourself exporting CSVs and building external dashboards because Vagaro's native multi-location reporting lacks the depth operators need for real decision-making. Payroll works fine until you have commission splits varying by service category, provider tenure, and location—then it becomes spreadsheet supplementation.

Here's what breaks at scale with Boulevard: your budget. We've seen Boulevard implementations running $12,000-$18,000 annually for a single busy location once you add memberships, the forms add-on, and premium support. The platform handles complexity beautifully, but you're paying luxury prices for that capability.

<div class="callout-blue">
<strong>Pro Tip:</strong> Before choosing either platform, document your commission structure completely. If it takes more than one page to explain, you need Boulevard. If you can summarize it in three bullet points, Vagaro handles it fine.
</div>

The integration ecosystem matters more than most operators realize during evaluation. Vagaro's native integrations cover basics well—QuickBooks, Mailchimp, standard marketing tools. Boulevard's API-first architecture enables deeper integrations with [CRM systems](/comparisons/spa-crm-software-comparison) and custom workflows, but you'll likely need developer resources to maximize it.

<h2 id="key-features">⚡ Key Features Compared</h2>

<h3 id="online-booking">Online Booking Experience</h3>

Vagaro's booking widget is functional but dated. Clients can book services, select providers, and complete payment, but the interface feels like 2019. Customization options exist but require CSS knowledge for meaningful brand alignment. The mobile app drives significant traffic—Vagaro's marketplace sends clients to providers, which Boulevard doesn't match.

Boulevard's booking flow is objectively superior. The interface feels premium, handles complex service combinations elegantly, and supports detailed intake forms within the booking process. For med spas where consultations and consent forms precede treatment, Boulevard's workflow eliminates manual touchpoints.

<h3 id="pos-checkout">POS and Checkout</h3>

Both platforms offer integrated payment processing. Vagaro charges 2.2% + $0.19 per transaction on their native processor, with options to integrate external terminals. Boulevard's processing runs 2.6% + $0.10 typically, though rates vary by volume.

The checkout experience diverges significantly. Vagaro handles standard spa transactions competently—services, retail, tips, splits. Boulevard anticipates upsells, handles partial redemptions of package credits elegantly, and provides checkout scripts for front desk staff.

<h3 id="membership-management">Membership and Package Management</h3>

This is where Boulevard pulls ahead dramatically. Vagaro's membership functionality covers basics—recurring charges, included services, member pricing. But managing complex membership tiers with rollover credits, family sharing, pause/resume logic, and location-specific benefits requires workarounds.

Boulevard built membership management as a core feature. Our team has implemented membership programs with 8+ tiers, location-specific benefits, automated renewal communications, and failed payment recovery sequences entirely within Boulevard. Vagaro required external tools and manual processes for comparable complexity.

<div class="callout-orange">
<strong>Warning:</strong> Migrating memberships between platforms is painful regardless of direction. Factor 40-60 hours of administrative work per 500 active members when planning any platform switch.
</div>

<h3 id="reporting-analytics">Reporting and Analytics</h3>

Vagaro provides 40+ standard reports covering revenue, appointments, payroll, inventory, and marketing. For single-location operators or small groups, these reports answer most operational questions adequately. Custom report building exists but lacks the flexibility sophisticated operators need.

Boulevard's reporting infrastructure handles questions Vagaro can't answer: revenue by room utilization, membership lifetime value by acquisition source, service profitability including provider time allocation. For operators running on data, Boulevard's analytics justify pricing premiums.

<h3 id="marketing-tools">Marketing and Client Communication</h3>

Vagaro includes email marketing, SMS campaigns, and automated reminders within base pricing. The tools are competent though not sophisticated—you're getting Mailchimp-lite functionality without additional subscription costs. The marketplace listing provides organic visibility competitors charge separately for.

Boulevard's marketing tools integrate more deeply with client data. Segmentation capabilities allow targeting based on service history, spend levels, and membership status. The platform supports [automated marketing workflows](/guides/spa-marketing-automation) that Vagaro requires external tools to replicate.

